			<ul>
				<li>Automatically annotate Japanese text with readings and
					translations.</li>
				<li>Export the annotated document and vocabulary list.</li>
				<li>Supports EDICT and Wadoku Jiten dictionaries.</li>
			</ul>

			<p>
				<a href="webstart/jnlp/jgloss.jnlp" class="btn btn-primary">Launch
					JGloss &raquo;</a>
		        <a href="download.html" class="btn">Download &raquo;</a>
		        <a href="details.html" class="btn">Read more &raquo;</a>
                <a href="http://www.java.com/download/" class="pull-right">Requires Java 7</a>
			</p>
		</div>

		<div class="row">
			<div class="span4">
				<h2><a href="details.html#Dictionaries">Dictionaries &raquo;</a></h2>
				<p>
                    JGloss supports the popular <a href="http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~jwb/edict_doc.html">EDICT2</a> dictionary file format.
                    Available dictionaries include the Japanese-English 
                    <a href="http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~jwb/edict.html">EDICT</a> itself, 
                    the Japanese-German <a href="http://www.wadoku.de/">Wadoku Jiten</a>, and many others. The
                    <a href="http://www.csse.monash.edu.au/~jwb/kanjidic.html">Kanjidic</a> dictionary format is also supported.
                </p>
			</div>
			<div class="span4">
				<h2><a href="examples.html">Examples &raquo;</a></h2>
				<p>
                    Have a look a the <a href="screenshots.html">screenshots</a> to see JGloss in action.
                    <a href="karinodouji/kari.pdf">This PDF document</a> is generated from a LaTeX file
                    generated by JGloss. Documents can also be exported as 
                    <a href="karinodouji/kari.html">HTML</a>. You can also save a
                    <a href="karinodouji/kari.annotations.txt">vocabulary list</a> as plain text.
                </p>
			</div>
			<div class="span4">
				<h2><a href="developing.html">Free Software &raquo;</a></h2>
